PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:Market Tone: Cautious ahead of Bernanke press conference. Dollar mixed, Treasurys lower, oil slightly higher, gold little changedOvernight Action: BP Net Profit Rises; S&P Changes Japan Outlook to Negative;Watch for: Fed rate decision and press conference,  earnings from Ebay, Starbucks, Boeing, ConocoPhillipsThe Breakfast BriefingToday, all eyes will go to the Bearded One.Federal Reserve Chairman Ben Bernanke will face the scribes in a first-ever press conference at 2:15 p.m. EDT. The Fed says the press conference is aimed at increasing transparency. It?s more likely to be a tour de force in sleep-inducing obfuscation.The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed?s policy group, will issue its statement at 1230 p.m. EDT, ahead of Big Ben?s 2:15 p.m. EDT date with the press. It is difficult to imagine that Big Ben will break new ground at the microphone, but there?s always hope. Jean-Claude Trichet, head of the European Central Bank, used a press briefing to signal that the ECB planned to raise rates this month, which it did early this month. (The ECB, like other central banks, has held press briefings for years.)The dollar?s recent weakness ? the dollar index is at a three-year low and the euro is at a fresh 52-week high ? underscores the belief that the Fed is in no rush to tighten its extraordinarily loose monetary policy. Our friends at Real Time Economics offer a nifty primer on how to interpret the words and phrases of Big Ben. (The over/under betting line for number of chuckles Big Ben gets: three.)The Fed, in its statement, is expected to say it will finish its $600 billion quantitative easing program (QE2) on schedule in June. It is also not expected to raise too many alarms about looming interest-rate moves. The Fed-funds futures sees only a 26% chance that the Fed will raise rates to 0.5% by next February.As investors fidget about what the Bearded One might say, earnings will come in full force once again. On Tuesday, strong earnings from 3M, Ford Motor, Delta Air Lines and UPS helped set a robust tone from the opening bell.The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 115.49 to 12595.37, its highest close since June 5, 2008. The Nasdaq Composite jumped 21.66 to 2847.54, its highest close since Oct. 31, 2007. And the S&P 500 gained 11.99 to 1347.24, its best close since June 17, 2008.On Wednesday, earnings will come from all directions, with energy and aerospace dominating.On the energy front, Baker Hughes, Cabot Oil & Gas, BP, ConocoPhillips, ENI, Hess Corp. and National Oil Well Varco report. Energy companies have reported strong earnings, boosted by rising oil prices. Boeing, General Dynamics and Northrop Grumman report on the aerospace side. Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Experts' expectations are downbeat

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The consensus of almost three dozen
    investment analysts is for a continuing bull market in stocks, with returns of eight to 10
    percent. Mutual fund analyst Kirk Kazanjian conducted the survey of market gurus,
    which included Elaine Garzarelli, technology guru Michael Murphy, newsletter
    editor Al Frank, and Forbes columnist David Dreman. "Overall, these
    experts still believe the stock market is the place to be," Kazanjian says.
    "They just don't expect the incredible ride we've been on for the past few years to
    continue. In essence, they're looking for a breather that could last into the new
    millennium." Kazanjian includes the analysts' thoughts in a new book, Wall Street's
    Picks for 1998. Previous editions have included valuable information. "In 1996, my
    investment panel accurately called for a strong bull market, even though the overall
    sentiment at the time was bearish," he notes. "Then in 1997, these advisors
    warned of a correction that would shave stock prices between 10 and 20 percent during the
    year, which was right again."
